  "opinion": "As a retired man from Kansas City who spent his life in vocational training and worked alongside my children in our small family business, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can shadow even the most capable individuals. Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's the quiet anxiety that lingers when someone feels they're being judged by others' expectations rather than their own potential. Growing up in a household where my father had only completed lower secondary education and my mother had upper secondary, I learned early that being labeled 'not smart enough' for math or science could be more damaging than any actual failure. In my decades of teaching and mentoring, I've noticed how this fear can make students hesitate to ask questions or push boundaries, especially when they're from backgrounds where STEM fields aren't traditionally seen as pathways to success. The truth is, stereotype threat should be addressed—it's not a problem to ignore. But the way we address it matters. We need to create environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of being categorized by their race, gender, or background. In my community, we've seen success when teachers and mentors take the time to listen without judgment, to share stories of their own struggles, and to celebrate the diversity of thought that makes STEM fields so rich. This isn't about changing the system overnight; it's about building a culture where every person feels they belong, whether they're climbing a rock, painting a canvas, or solving a complex equation.",
